Third Avenue, west side, south from E. 37th Street. At the left is the Third Avenue "El" structure straddling the surface car tracks. Note the Belgium block pavement and the grade to the right leading uphill to Lexington Avenue.

Third Avenue, east side, south from E. 38th Street, showing mainly the 38th-37th Street frontage as viewed southeastward from the N. W. corner.

January 7, 1939

Somach Photo Service
New York City Tunnel Authority

212 to 220 E. 37th Street, south side, east of Third Avenue, showing several loft buildings. To the right and partially shown is No. 212. Adjoining same is a dual structure No. 214-216. The building bearing the date 1885 is No. 218-220. All of these are to the rear of B. Altman's garage and warehouse.

January 16, 1939

Somach Photo Service
New York City Tunnel Authority

211, 215 and 221-27 E. 37th Street, north side, east of Third Avenue, showing the Jarcho Building which may be demolished. This is an 8 story structure that has only recently replaced 3 former 3 story tenements. A vacant lot (former 4 story No. 219) separates this from the New York Telephone Company Building. Note the construction activity at the latter necessitated by an easterly addition of similar height replacing former tenements, No's 229-231.

(1) East 37th Street, south side, east from (No. 203), apoint slightly east of Third Avenue, showing preparation for the Midtown-Queens tunnel entrance. This will be in the foreground and slope gradually to pass under Second Avenue ("El" line). Beyond same appears the cleared block extending to First Avenue. A plaza is to be constructed there.
